1. Add a `data-search-url` attribute to the input field that contains the URL of the search endpoint in your Rails app:
```html
<input type="text" id="search-navbar" class="block w-full p-2 pl-10 text-sm text-gray-900 border border-gray-300 rounded-lg bg-gray-50 focus:ring-blue-500 focus:border-blue-500 dark:bg-gray-700 dark:border-gray-600 dark:placeholder-gray-400 dark:text-white dark:focus:ring-blue-500 dark:focus:border-blue-500" placeholder="Search..." data-search-url="<%= search_path %>">
```
In this example, `search_path` is a Rails route helper that points to your search endpoint.

1. Add some JavaScript code to your application that listens for changes to the input field and triggers an AJAX request to your server to fetch the search results. Here's an example using jQuery:
```javascript
$(function() {
  $('#search-navbar').on('input', function() {
    var query = $(this).val();
    var url = $(this).data('search-url');
    if (query.length > 2) {
      $.ajax({
        url: url,
        data: { q: query },
        success: function(data) {
          // Process the search results
        },
        error: function() {
          // Handle errors
        }
      });
    }
  });
});
```
In this example, we're using the `on` method to listen for the `input` event on the `#search-navbar` input field. When the event is triggered, we get the value of the input field and the search URL from the `data-search-url` attribute. We then check if the query is at least 3 characters long (you can adjust this to suit your needs), and if so, we make an AJAX request to the search endpoint with the query parameter `q` set to the value of the input field. When the server responds with the search results, we can process them in the `success` callback.

Note that this is just a basic example and you will likely need to modify it to suit your specific needs. For example, you may need to handle pagination of search results or add some UI feedback to let the user know that a search is in progress.

